\end{equation}
The curve $C$ can be parametrized using the following equation:
\begin{equation}
\vec{r}(s) = u(s)\hat{u} + v(s)\hat{v}, \text{where } 0 \le s \le 1, u(0)=a_x, v(0)=b_y, u(1)=b_x, v(1)=a_y
\end{equation}
We will use this parameterization for the calculation of the integral.

To calculate the derivative of the radius vector with respect to arc length, we first write it in terms of its components:
\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{ds}\left(\sqrt{u^2+v^2}\right) = \frac{du}{ds}\hat{u} + \frac{dv}{ds}\hat{v}
\end{equation}
Now, we substitute the above expression for $(dr/ds)$ into the integrand:
\begin{align}
&\frac{1}{|r|^3} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{u^2 + v^2}}\\
&\frac{d}{ds}\left(\frac{1}{|r|^3}\right) & = -3\frac{(u/|r|^2)(dr/ds)}{(|r|^4)^2} \\
& & & -3\frac{(v/|r|^2)(dr/ds)}{(|r|^4)^2}
\end{align}
Next, we take the curl of both sides of the previous equation:
\begin{align}
&\curl\left(\frac{1}{|r|^3}\right) & = -\frac{6}{|r|^5}\times (u/|r|^2) \\
&\curl\left(\frac{d}{ds}\left(\frac{1}{|r|^3}\right)\right) &=-\frac{6}{|r|^5}\times (u/|r|^2)(dr/ds)
\end{align}
Finally, we integrate both sides of the last equation over the entire loop $C$:
\begin{align}
&\oint_{C}\curl\left(\frac{1}{|r|^3}\right) & &=\oint_{C}\frac{6}{|r|^5}\times (u/|r|^2)ds \\
&\oint_{C}\curl\left(\frac{d}{ds}\left(\frac{1}{|r|^3}\right)\right) & &=\oint_{C}-\frac{6}{|r|^5}\times (u/|r|^2)(dr/ds)ds
\end{align}
After simplifying the left side of the last equation, we get:
\begin{align}
I & = 2\pi\cdot\frac{6}{|r_A-r_B|^5}\times (u(1)/(r_A-r_B)^2) - 2\pi\cdot\frac{6}{|r_A-r_B|^5}\times (u(0)/(r_A-r_B)^2)\\
& &=\frac{2\pi}{|r_A-r_B|^5}\times |u(1)-u(0)|
\end{align}
So, the final result for the integral is:
\begin{equation}
I = \frac{2\pi}{|r_A-r_B|^5}\times |u(1)-u(0)|
\end{equation}
Note that $r_A=(u(0),v(0))=a$, $r_B=(u(1),v(1))=b$, and $u(1)-u(0) = b_x-a_x$. Substituting these values, we get:
\begin{equation}
I = \frac{2\pi}{|b_x-a_x|^5}\times |b_x-a_x|
\end{equation}
Therefore, the integral we were looking for is equal to:
\begin{equation}
I = 2\pi\times\frac{1}{|b_x-a_x|^5}
\end{equation}</s>

